&lt;h3 id="install-openssh-server">Install OpenSSH server&lt;a class="td-heading-self-link" href="#install-openssh-server" aria-label="Heading self-link">&lt;/a>&lt;/h3>
&lt;p>Read through the following help pages:&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Reviving a dead Gigabyte MJ11-EC1 mainboard</title><link>https://kittenlabs.de/blog/2023/11/16/reviving-a-dead-gigabyte-mj11-ec1-mainboard/</link><pubDate>Thu, 16 Nov 2023 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://kittenlabs.de/blog/2023/11/16/reviving-a-dead-gigabyte-mj11-ec1-mainboard/</guid><description>&lt;p>Used Gigabyte MJ11-EC1 mainboards are available for low prices on ebay and at other hardware vendors.&lt;br>
After buying a couple of MJ11-EC1 boards for a homelab cluster project, I ended up with a dead board.&lt;br>
The server would turn on, BMC was reachable and could be used, but the server itself would never POST.&lt;br>
There were no POST codes, no beeps and no signs of life whatsoever.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Memory was tested (and OK), still swapped for a different DIMM, no change. CPU Vcore was present and stable.&lt;br>
Reflashing the BIOS image with the BMC didn&amp;rsquo;t change the behaviour either.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Dead TROTEC PAC2000S air conditioner</title><link>https://kittenlabs.de/blog/2022/08/24/dead-trotec-pac2000s-air-conditioner/</link><pubDate>Wed, 24 Aug 2022 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://kittenlabs.de/blog/2022/08/24/dead-trotec-pac2000s-air-conditioner/</guid><description>&lt;div class="alert alert-primary" role="alert">
&lt;h4 class="alert-heading">Safety note&lt;/h4>

 The A/C is being powered by a ST VIPER12A switch mode supply. This type of supply is &lt;em>not&lt;/em> mains-isolated, so all voltages (even the low voltages) are referenced to mains voltage.&lt;br>
Don&amp;rsquo;t work on this device while plugged in without being aware of the implications of this!&lt;br>
&lt;strong>Every metal piece, every wire, every component inside can be at deadly voltage potentials against mains earth!&lt;/strong>&lt;br>
Don&amp;rsquo;t connect any mains-referenced measurement equipment (like oscilloscopes), as &lt;a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sI5Ftm1-jik&amp;amp;t=140s" target="_blank">they&amp;rsquo;ll create a short-circuit and damage things&lt;/a>.

&lt;/div>

&lt;p>As &lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Murphy%27s_law" target="_blank">Murphy&amp;rsquo;s law&lt;/a> dictates, my portable A/C unit suddenly died while in operation on the hottest day of the summer.&lt;br>
No smoke, no explosion, just suddenly turned off and was then completely dead. No lights, no beeps, nothing.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>PlutoSDR standalone ADS-B FR24 feeder</title><link>https://kittenlabs.de/blog/2021/12/01/plutosdr-standalone-ads-b-fr24-feeder/</link><pubDate>Wed, 01 Dec 2021 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://kittenlabs.de/blog/2021/12/01/plutosdr-standalone-ads-b-fr24-feeder/</guid><description>&lt;p>PlutoSDR (or ADALM-PLUTO) is an inexpensive SDR (software-defined radio) platform by Analog Devices.
It uses a Xilinx Zynq Z-7010 FPGA, which integrates an 32bit ARMv7 core together with the FPGA functionality.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>This 32bit ARMv7 CPU runs Linux and is normally (when used as an SDR via USB) just passing libiio messages to the host computer.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>The USB port on the PlutoSDR can also be used as a host/OTG port instead. By connecting a USB-to-Ethernet converter and a USB flash drive (or other form of storage), the PlutoSDR can be a standalone Linux machine, just like a Raspberry Pi (or similar single board computer).&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Micro8088 build log</title><link>https://kittenlabs.de/blog/2020/10/29/micro8088-build-log/</link><pubDate>Thu, 29 Oct 2020 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://kittenlabs.de/blog/2020/10/29/micro8088-build-log/</guid><description>&lt;h3 id="overview">Overview&lt;a class="td-heading-self-link" href="#overview" aria-label="Heading self-link">&lt;/a>&lt;/h3>
&lt;p>This is a build log of an IBM XT-compatible system called &amp;ldquo;&lt;a href="https://github.com/skiselev/micro_8088" target="_blank">Micro 8088&lt;/a>&amp;rdquo;, designed by Sergey Kiselev.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>&lt;img src="IMG_0005.JPG" width="49%" alt="micro8088 CPU card, sitting in a ISA backplane"> &lt;img src="IMG_0010.JPG" width="49%" alt="Side view onto full micro8088 setup, with sound and video cards">&lt;/p>
