&lt;img src="tp820/IMG_5379.JPG" width="49%" alt="Connectors on the backside of a ThinkPad 820"> &lt;img src="tp820/IMG_5395.JPG" width="49%" alt="Connectors on the right side of the ThinkPad 820, PCMCIA, PS/2, power switch">&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>PlutoSDR clock input</title><link>https://kittenlabs.de/blog/2019/01/05/plutosdr-clock-input/</link><pubDate>Sat, 05 Jan 2019 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://kittenlabs.de/blog/2019/01/05/plutosdr-clock-input/</guid><description>&lt;p>&lt;strong>Warning!&lt;/strong> This modification &lt;a href="https://twitter.com/robinlgetz/status/1112011240770072579" target="_blank">voids the warranty&lt;/a> and can operate the transceiver outside of it&amp;rsquo;s &lt;a href="https://www.analog.com/media/en/technical-documentation/data-sheets/AD9364.pdf" target="_blank">absolute maximum ratings&lt;/a>!&lt;/p>
&lt;img src="featured-IMG_4119.jpg" width="49%" alt="PlutoSDR with 3rd SMA jack for clock input"> 
&lt;p>The PlutoSDR has an internal XO (&lt;a href="https://ez.analog.com/cfs-file/__key/telligent-evolution-components-attachments/00-323-01-00-00-08-92-34/attachment.pdf" target="_blank">Rakon RXO3225M 40.000 MHz&lt;/a>), which has excellent qualities like very low jitter.&lt;br>
Unfortunatly for ham radio use, the absolute accuracy (PPM) and stability isn&amp;rsquo;t great.&lt;br>
When generating signals in the GHz-range (like a TX-signal for QO-100 at 2.4 GHz) the error can multiply up to several kHz,
much more than the signal bandwidth itself.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>WiFi over satellite TV coax</title><link>https://kittenlabs.de/blog/2018/10/14/wifi-over-satellite-tv-coax/</link><pubDate>Sun, 14 Oct 2018 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://kittenlabs.de/blog/2018/10/14/wifi-over-satellite-tv-coax/</guid><description>&lt;p>There&amp;rsquo;s a number of different ways to distribute an ethernet signal throughout a building.
The most common types being:&lt;/p>
&lt;ul>
&lt;li>twisted pair wiring&lt;/li>
&lt;li>fiber optic cable&lt;/li>
&lt;li>WiFi (2.4 GHz, 5GHz)&lt;/li>
&lt;li>powerline (also called PLC, IEEE 1901)&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>
&lt;p>In my application, running cables wasn&amp;rsquo;t easily possible, so twisted pair and fiber connections were out of the game. PLC-based networking is absolutely unacceptable as a ham radio operator, because these devices produce lots of interference and noise.
The distance is a bit too big to utilize &amp;ldquo;regular&amp;rdquo; WiFi links, so a different solution was needed.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Search Results</title><link>https://kittenlabs.de/search/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://kittenlabs.de/search/</guid><description/></item></channel></rss>